  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>RUNNING FROM RAZBUK</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p>I had discovered that a Troll, who believes he has me in his debt, had arrived in Freeport to collect on that supposed debt.  As I had no time to escape, I went into hiding.  This vicious child of Grobb had allies in all corners of the city and eyes watching every exit.</p>

<p>I had been in hiding for several weeks when I
reached the resolution that I had to take my chances, trust in fate, and leave the city.  I chose my best illusion, disguising myself as a human.  I chose an unremarkable face and held carefully to the illusion as I walked calmly toward the west gate.  I was just passing a small wagon set up near the gate by a rogue Ogre when I heard a familiar voice from behind me.</p>

<p>"So, me am fin' yu fin'ly, Baggza!"  My knees nearly failed me.  It was Razbuk.  "Now me am take yu an' am git me munny frum yu.  Yu in big trubble now!"</p>

<p>I continued walking, hoping to convince him that
he had the wrong human.  It was to no avail.  As the Freeport guards looked on, snickering, ruffians of many of the races of Norrath surrounded me.  Razbuk had apparently recruited quite an assortment of friends.  I looked around, trying to find some avenue of escape, but none presented itself.  Razbuk had me.  I began to cast a spell, hoping to stun them, but the vile Troll gave a shouted order and his friends moved in and began to attack me.  Unable to concentrate on my spell under the rain of blows, I fell to the ground.  My last thought before everything went black was that I hoped one of the gods would see fit to return my life to me after these monsters took it away.</p>

<p>I awoke and realized that the gods had not
brought me back to life.  My first clue was that every part of my body was sore.  My second was that I could smell Razbuk's foul odor near me.  I opened my eyes and got my third clue.  I was tied up and sitting in the corner of a stone room.</p>

<p>There was a small fire in one corner and a pot
sat upon it.  There was a vile odor emanating from that direction.  I looked around and saw Razbuk, sitting on a massive chair.  His right pointer finger was jammed into his ear and he sat there, making an awful humming noise while he dug away.  He had not yet mustered the concentration to realize that I was awake.</p>

<p>I tried to think of a way to escape.  My
illusion was gone, and he, being a shaman, would surely know as soon as I tried to cast any sort of spell.  His chair sat between me and the door, and I knew I could not run by him.  I decided that I would try to reason with him.</p>

<p>"So, now that you have me, what are you
going to do?"  I asked it with some hesitancy, hoping to seem cowed.  Although how he was supposed to realize what that sounded like, I have no idea.</p>

<p>His hand jerked away from his ear and he looked
at me with those slightly vacant eyes.  The purple one seemed larger today, although how the two eyes could alternate sizes was still a mystery to me.</p>

<p>His words interrupted my thoughts.  "Me
tink yu am gonna tel me what yu do wif mie munny."  He snorted and glared at me, as if to emphasize his point.</p>

<p>I sighed.  "Look, even if I had taken
your money, why would I tell you what I did with it?  And how do you know I haven't spent it already?"</p>

<p>"Yu is gon' tel me 'cuz udder-utter-err...'cuz if not me is gon' eat yu."</p>

<p>"Such a marvelous plan."  I rolled
my eyes.  "Do tell, if you eat me before I tell you where your fictitious money is, how ever will you find it?"</p>

<p>"Razbuk am smart.  Me 'no how two fin'
tings.  Me am get me munny back wif or wifouchur help."</p>

<p>"Really?  I seriously doubt you could find your fingers and toes in the morning if they weren't already attached.  In fact, why don't I save you the trouble of eating me and then searching blindly for your money by just showing you where it is?"</p>

<p>The troll's green eye widened at this and he
grinned.  It was a sickening sight.  "Yu take Razbuk to were yu hid me munny and me is letting yu go."</p>

<p>And so, I found myself in the company of Razbuk
and four or five of his flunkies, traveling through the Commonlands west of Freeport, and trying to decide how I was going to get out of this.</p>

<p>I needed to find someplace where I could buy the
time to get away.  The Freeport guards were obviously on the side of Razbuk and his friends.  That's not saying much.  The Freeport guards seem to be on the side of whoever gives them the most money.  But I digress.</p>

<p>I led Razbuk to the extreme west edge of the
commonlands, where the dark forest of Kithicor began.  I had ventured inside before and found it to my liking, during the daytime.  As we approached, a plan began to form itself in my head.  I led the thieves inside the forest.</p>

<p>Razbuk objected, but I explained that we would be
in and out before dark.  He seemed satisfied with this.  His men did not seem to understand our little conversation.  They had never been inside the Kithicor Wood before.  As we marched through the forest, I explained to them the dangers of the night.  These were hard men, but I saw them flinch as I told of the armies of the undead that rise from the ground every night to do the bidding of their lord Innoruuk.  By the time we reached the cave leading to Rivervale, I was certain that most of them wanted to turn back.</p>

<p>"I have hidden the money away in this
city," I patiently explained to my captor.  "I must go in and retrieve it, for I have a few acquaintances who guard it for me."</p>

<p>"Dat soun gud to me.  Me not go in dere
cuz dem lital ones hurt me gud once.   Yu take Razbuk friends wif yu."</p>

<p>This was what I expected but hoped to avoid. 
"I've never visited these acquaintances with anyone else, and they might take it as odd that I come with a group of five.  Perhaps if only one were to go with me?"  I thought it was a good compromise.</p>

<p>Razbuk grunted.  "Me no lik dat. 
Yu ken kil one of Razbuk friends alone.  Yu take al of dem or yu not go an me eat yu insted."</p>

<p>"Hmmm...  What if your friends watch
from a ways off?"</p>

<p>He seemed to think about this for a moment, and
then grunted his consent.  "Yu go in wif one, de rest, dey follow yu and watch two make shur yu don' try to trik Razbuk."</p>

<p>"OK.  I'll need to use one of my
illusion spells, of course."  Razbuk nodded and I began to cast Illusion: Gnome.  I knew my friends inside would recognize me in that guise.</p>

<p>I led the way, knowing that I was almost there and had better not slip up now.  The halflings had carved tunnels and paths everywhere possible, and town seemed more like a rabbit warren that a city.  I took several out-of-the-way turns, hoping to lose the rest of my honor guard, and finally arrived at the house I sought.</p>

<p>Kizzie stood there, as usual, at her store counter.  She sold all sorts of goods that could only be found or made from ingredients found in the Misty Thicket.  I winked at her once on the way in, something I had never done before, and hoped that she would understand the signal for what it was.  My jailer had a bit of trouble fitting through the low door, but he came in and situated himself.</p>

<p>"Ah, Baggza, I see you've brought yourself a
friend.  How nice!"  Her tone showed nothing.  "Would you like the usual today?  And a Honey Jum for your friend, as well?"</p>

<p>"Actually, Kizzie, I've come for something
different today.  Do you remember that bag I asked you to hold onto for me?  The one with my rock collection in it?"</p>

<p>"Aye, Baggza, I remember it.  I've
never opened it, just like you said.  You know you can trust me with anything."  She crossed her fingers over her heart in the little people's symbol of friendship and trust.</p>

<p>"That I do, friend.  Do you mind if I
take it back now, out of your fireplace?  I want to show those rocks to a friend of mine."</p>

<p>"Not at all.  Not a problem at all."  She led us back to the fireplace in the corner of one of the dug-out rooms of her cottage.  The fireplace had a bit of ash on the ground, and I reached down as if to pull up the stone beneath.</p>

<p>"Mind helping me with this rock, friend?  It's quite heavy."  Razbuk's guard looked perplexed for a moment, then seemed to understand.  He bent down to help me lift the stone.</p>

<p>At that moment, I released the spell I had covered with my illusion, and a gust of wind knocked the small pile of ashes into his face.  He reached to his eyes just as Kizzie hit him over the head with a broomstick and he collapsed to the floor.</p>

<p>"I hope that was worth all the trouble we
went to, Baggza."  Kizzie looked somewhat doubtful about that.</p>

<p>"He works for a troll who is trying to kill
me.  The creature thinks I owe him money.  It is a long story.  You can report to the deputies that he threatened me with violence and I had to react.  They'll put him in jail for a time, I'll wager."</p>

<p>She seemed satisfied with this explanation and I
asked if I could use the back door to leave.  There were others, and they would surely pounce on me if I left without their friend.  She walked me to the door and reassured me that she would take care of him.</p>

<p>As soon as the door was shut, I cast another Illusion, this time Halfling, and made myself look like a distant relative of Kizzie's.  I then half-skipped around to the front of the cottage and back out the cave whence I had come.  Razbuk's friends were watching the door carefully, but trying not to be too obvious about it.  They didn't even notice me.</p>

<p>I reached the cave and skipped around the corner to find Razbuk there.  I screamed, "Troll!" and ran to the guards.  They ran out the cave after Razbuk, and, from what I could tell, chased him quite a ways before they gave up.</p>

<p>I gated back to Freeport and immediately assumed one of my favorite guises, that of a traveling storyteller, and set off toward the Oasis.  I believe Razbuk ran all the way back to Grobb, for he has not bothered me again.</p> </font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><small>By <b>Baggza</b> Submited on 3/13/2001</small></td>
	</tr>
